WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Do we want to change discs?

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:24.000
When we reach sort of natural partying spots, because these are digital files, we'll stop to save the files.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:30.000
So they don't get too long, because the one will interrupt you.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:37.000
I'll start by giving you an introduction for the tape, but then we'll just want to write it.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Today is Sunday April 14, 2013. This is David Klein for the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:54.000
The Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of African American History and Culture of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:04.000
And again, this is David Klein interviewer. I'm here with John Bishop, videographer, and I'm very happy to have with us today Gloria Claudette Grinnell.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
And thank you so much for being part of this project. We very much appreciate your time.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
Thank you for coming.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:23.000
So if I could ask you, if we could just start with your childhood, if you could tell us a little bit about your family and where you were raised, and the environment that you came out of.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Okay. I'll go back to my grandparents if I may, because in a way it was a civil rights type activity.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:41.000
My grandfather, this is stories that were told to me, and I asked my cousin about it because he is older than I, and he says it's true.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:52.000
My grandfather had $500 invested in the stock market, and of course he lost it. This is when people were jumping out the window and so forth.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:01.000
And my grandparents were teachers. I think he taught languages and music, and I don't know what my grandmother taught.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:16.000
But they moved from Virginia to Philadelphia. And that started the family, split the family, because my grandparents couldn't get a job. They said they didn't hire black teachers in Philly.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.000
They had black children going to integrated schools, but no black teachers.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:35.000
So my grandmother took in washing, and my grandfather refused to do that type work. And the family actually split. They were together physically, but not together.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:45.000
The older kids went to college in the family, and they were teachers at two oldest ones.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:52.000
The youngest kid was sent to school by the middle children who did not go to college. They had to work to help pay.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:03:05.000
So, but again, here we go about the color line thing. I was born in DC. My mother was born in Virginia, and my dad was born in Maryland.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:17.000
And when I was three, oh, my parents divorced when I was a baby. And my dad took the boy, my mother took the girl, and remarried, moved to San Francisco.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:34.000
So from the age of three on, I grew up in San Francisco. Then she remarried again, and moved to San Diego. And I ended up at Virginia Union University, which one of my great, great grandparents was on the board at Virginia.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And it was great to know that my great, great, great, grandparent had helped to start the school.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:58.000
So, if we talk a little bit more about your childhood growing up on the West Coast, before you went to experience Virginia.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:05.000
And what were the sort of racial dynamics of life in both Southern and also the Northern California?

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:14.000
Okay, growing up in San Francisco, I lived in what is now called the Western Addition. It was called the Western Addition back in those days.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:25.000
You know, and I tried to think, was it full of black people? I think as a child, you probably don't even know. And I guess that's where the black people lived.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Then we moved to the Presidio.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:37.000
And I went to St. Dominic's own Pine and Steiner, if you know where that is. It was all white. I was only black child.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:46.000
And every day I used to pray, I hope the nun doesn't slap me this morning. She would walk down as we were praying outside in the morning and slap me.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:56.000
And I, we prayed to God, God, I've done something wrong. Please help me. You know, I didn't know what I had done wrong. Never did.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:03.000
And I used to get F's. All my papers were F's. And I, I was in the second grade or third grade.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And my mother said, you need to bring your papers home and I started crying. She said, what's wrong? I said, mom, I'm dumb. I get all F's.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:20.000
She said, that's okay. Bring them home anyway. She collected that many papers about an inch and marched me up to the school. And she says, why are these marked wrong?

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:35.000
There's nothing wrong on most of the pay. I didn't know I was bright. And the nun started crying. And my mom said, go outside and play. I said, mom, I'm not allowed to play. I have to go to church doing recess and lunch.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
What are the other kids for outplay?

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:49.000
And my mother says, I think you better go outside. I don't know what she said to the nun, but after that, the smartest girl and I in class were vying for grades.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:55.000
And then then stopped slapping me. I didn't tell my mother she slapped me.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:11.000
So that was my experience there. I went to a public school first called Presidio. And a little boy said, a little white boy. A little boy said that he couldn't hold my hand because his mother said he couldn't hold a hand of niggers.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:20.000
So I went home and asked my mother was I a nigger because I didn't know. I knew it was something bad because he couldn't hold my hand.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
So that was probably the first time you heard that.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:36.000
Yeah. That was my experience there. I had heard of other experiences. I remember we owned a mom and pops grocery store, which is typical in San Francisco.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:44.000
You know, they have a safe way, but generally you have little stories. And a man came in and my parents never talked in front of me.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:53.000
And then I heard them whispering that he's a teacher, but he can only substitute because he has a dishonable discharge.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:01.000
Because during World War II, he jumped off a ship refusing to fight because he said, why should he fight for America?

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Freeing other countries, whether he's not free here. I remember that was saying that.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:18.000
And then I remember my mother trying to get a job and they told her you join the union first and you can get the job.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:29.000
And the union says get the job first and vice versa. This went on. And I remember my mother crying, but not in front of us, but I do remember.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:41.000
So little things, subtle things. You know, you know, Santa Monica had a big rope across their beach, you know, unofficially, but it's there.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:52.000
You know, teaching jobs, only teaching the black area. You know, I mean, it was there. It's still there, but.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:08:04.000
So when had your parents at all prepared you for what it would be like, as you got ready to go across the country.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:13.000
No, nobody could prepare you. You didn't know the first thing I did when I got in town. I sat down at the soda fountain. I said, gee, I want to banal split. I'll never forget this.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:24.000
One strawberry, one vanilla. And if you don't have black walnut, please put another strawberry, no chocolate and and strawberry syrup on top and whipped cream in that.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:33.000
I always get that. The lady went away to make it and she came back and she says, oh, we can't serve you. I said, oh, are you out?

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:48.000
She says, no, and I said, oh, I remember saying, oh, I said, oh, three times it shocked me. You know, I couldn't get a banal split because I'm black sitting at the counter.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:53.000
I wasn't thinking. I knew you couldn't, but I wasn't thinking. I just sat down.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:09:07.000
Yeah. Yeah. Had you had experiences like that in California? They are overt, not covert. You can fill them. Yeah. Yeah.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:19.000
But there it was just. Yeah. Well, I have been asked when I went to high school, my cousin was Filipino. And she says, Claudette, I want you, my middle name is Claudette.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:31.000
I want you to come with me to the Filipino picnic. I said, no, I'm not Filipino. I said, you are. She says, come with me. So I went and I took my date.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:41.000
And when we got to the place outside of San Francisco, the guy said on the on the gate, I have to let you in. Are you sure you want to come?

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:53.000
So I've had that type thing or places in you people can come in. Do you think you're going to be happy? You know, yeah.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:59.000
Kind of coded or presented. Right. Right.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:07.000
May I ask why you decided to go to a black, traditionally black? Yeah. My mother thought it would be good for me.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:17.000
I know. But you know, I think a black, I think I should have gone to Howard. I mean, don't get me wrong for genuine union was great. But I should have been in the city.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:26.000
You know, because it was too much learning at one time, being in the south and the mentality and.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:32.000
So what was that that like when we talked about those people, but what was that the indoctrination till?

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:38.000
Well, I didn't like anybody, the black people and the white people.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:47.000
It was it. First of all, I was young and I thought I knew everything and I didn't. I didn't know anything.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:51.000
And this is what you're you got?

00:10:51.000 --> 00:11:04.000
In the 50s, 50, 59 around then. But you know, as a young person, you're very ignorant, but you don't know it.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:16.000
I thought I knew everything. And when I went there, I couldn't understand why the white people treated the blacks away. They were treated. And why the blacks allowed it.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:30.000
I even got angry with some of the black people for not sitting in the kids. And I didn't understand. I do now. If they had sat in, they wouldn't have had done on the table that night because their parents would have been fired.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:34.000
I had no idea.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:42.000
So what was Virginia Union University like in terms of a sort of a consciousness of black consciousness that was among.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:49.000
Or even where there are teachers that were talking about these issues.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:57.000
Yeah, I you know, I believe people it was a way of life. And they knew how to live within the system.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:07.000
I'm not saying it was comfortable for them, but I think they had a black society, which was a way of living.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:14.000
I remember Dr. Johnson, who was my favorite instructor there, Bob Johnson. He had two PhDs, I think.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:27.000
I think he got his first when he was 18, I'm not sure. Very bright man. He used to play in a quartet. I don't know what he played violin or something.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:39.000
He said one night he was driving home. He used to tell jokes in class. And he had this white woman in car. Then he thought, oh my God, I'm going to be killed. He was always saying things like that.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:46.000
I don't know. I don't remember. I'm so dag on old. I don't remember.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:13:02.000
So I'm going to be asking questions about this. The city has been obviously curious what prefigured those, what kind of conversations you may have been having amongst yourselves as students.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:14.000
Well, we were having meetings as you know, Charles and Pinkett, what's his name? Charles Sherrod /, I think. We're the leaders. And we were always having meetings about that.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:18.000
Charles, you're off.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
Can you remember what some of those meetings were like?

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:27.000
No, I can't. I'm telling you, being old is a son of a gun.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:43.000
But I thought the world was going to change, though. I was so naive. Gosh. I remember going, the policeman, the police person was very nice to me. I remember when we were arrested, he held my hand and helped me up into the Paddy wagon.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:52.000
And I thought that was so nice. Am I aren't called me? She says, I see you on the news. You're being helped into the Paddy wagon.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:56.000
And you mentioned that there are some students who didn't participate that you were angry with.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:07.000
I was angry with them because I felt they lived in Virginia they should. But then after meeting, I met one girl at the reunion.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:12.000
I'm cold and I'm kind of freezing. Can you stop a minute? Yeah.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:26.000
Okay. I met a lady at the 50th year reunion. Well, she was in the sit-in, so every day I knew her. But they needed pictures. I didn't remember anyone. They needed pictures when they were young.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:40.000
Because I haven't seen these people in 50 years. And we were sitting at the table and tears were coming down her eyes. I felt like crying too, but I don't cry in front of people.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:53.000
And she said that her father was fired. They had to move out of state. She had to drop out of school. I don't know if she ever finished college. And I thought, you know, that's how naive I was.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:15:01.000
She was one of the Virginia people, a few people from Virginia were in the sit-ins. What quite a few I'm sure. But I wanted all of them to be in there.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:07.000
But I didn't live in Virginia. My parents were in California, you know.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:19.000
So you talked about thinking you're going to change the world. What did you want to change? Well, I thought I know that we're not all going to be a hunky-dory, but I thought, well, it's going to be integration now.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:32.000
You know, it's not going to. The first thing I did, I remember when we got arrested, we went to a courthouse. And I mean, I'm sorry, went to jail. And they put us in this cell, all of us. And it was smelly.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:46.000
And I thought, dog, gone in. Not even a clean cell can you go in. And then in the court, the court was segregated. I felt like, am I in hell? What has happened? I mean, even the courts are segregated.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:16:01.000
And then I remember a black man came in and he was a drunkard and you could smell him. And I thought, why do the judges have to come in? You know, I'm thinking, just it's going downhill fast.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:20.000
And I thought, am I losing my mind? You know, you know, horrible. But I just thought, okay, now that we've sat in, we have these attorneys and they're going to go to court and everything is going to be right. And it's not going to be any longer.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:30.000
But you can change laws, but you can't change people. It comes about through your doing individually.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:34.000
And that's what kind of process is that?

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
What do you think?

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:57.000
You know, I think, well, the young kids today, many of them didn't grow up during that era. Thank God. And many of them, if you get angry with anyone, it's angry, not because of a person's color, it's for some other reason.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:09.000
And I think that's great. Many of the kids are that way today. You know, I mean, you still have, you're going to always have an upper dog and a lower dog. You know.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:12.000
How long were you at college before the 7th started?

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:18.000
I don't remember. You're asking me difficult questions.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:22.000
This is the pre-example.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:30.000
I'm sorry. Really, I don't remember. In fact, I was surprised that it was so important.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:47.000
Well, this would have been, so the Senate Virginia Union University was, or with Virginia Union University students, was about, I believe about three weeks after the one that, in Greensboro,

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.000
they were on February 1st.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:59.000
And so it would have been one of the early ones, but part of the wave of citizens. Do you know if you were aware of where, you know, other citizens?

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:03.000
Yeah. Why did this come up as a strategy?

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:07.000
Yeah. I don't, honest to Pete. I really don't remember.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:11.000
But you were aware of the thing you got here.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:20.000
What about the notion of nonviolence and how you were going to comport yourselves, could potentially be dangerous?

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:29.000
Yeah. I was going to be a nonviolent person. I'm not a violent person anyway, just my mouth, unfortunately.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:37.000
Yeah. I thought it's not fair to have people hit you.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:46.000
And you can't really protect yourself. It's really not fair. I think had I been a man, I probably would have been angry and retaliated.

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:50.000
I don't know that, but maybe.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:53.000
And where's their report?

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:59.000
Did you run into trauma? No. The dogs and things, but it was fine.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:07.000
When I said it was fine, our citizens were calm compared to some other cities and other cities and states.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:10.000
What actually happened?

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:17.000
We went downtown several days and we went to Thalhimer's department store and we sat down.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:23.000
Well, I didn't sit down. I was standing, but being so tall, they pointed me out really intruly.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:31.000
Because I stand out and I had on high heels shoes too. So that made me over six feet tall.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:40.000
And they just wouldn't serve us. I mean, it was relatively calm compared to what I've seen on the news and talked with other people.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:45.000
How many students were there? 34.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:49.000
And you went where you were arrested right away or did it take you?

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:55.000
We walked. The first day, the first time we weren't the second time we were. We walked from school to downtown.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:01.000
It was kind of a, I hate to say this, but a jovial mood, you know, a lot of kids walking together.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:05.000
I guess we're all going to change the world.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:11.000
I don't know how they felt, but that's the attitude that I had and the feeling that I got.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:13.000
Or were there songs being sung or anything like that?

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:17.000
Yeah, and don't ask me the name so quickly.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:25.000
Not only that, I had to learn black culture. Not that I, you know, I had to learn the black songs.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:31.000
Growing up a Catholic, which I'm no longer growing up a Catholic, you don't know those songs.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:35.000
I had never heard the black national anthem before in my life.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:43.000
A lot of things I had to learn. I remember I went to Adam Clayton Powell was a big man.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:47.000
And he and my uncle worked together too.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:52.000
And he came to town to talk. And I went to one of his meetings, civil rights meetings.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:59.000
And in the church, the people clapped and they banged their feet like this and it scared me.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:05.000
I don't want this on the thing. I had never been in a whole group of black people.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:11.000
And can you imagine I'm black and I'm scared? I mean, that doesn't make good sense.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:15.000
But you've never experienced this before.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:17.000
No.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:23.000
So you said earlier that when you first got to Virginia, and there's this sort of not liking the black people, not liking the white people?

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:27.000
Did this change for you as really long?

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:35.000
I got a better understanding of what was happening.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:39.000
But the black people had to live there.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:45.000
And the white people were only going along with the status quo.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:51.000
And I know I was getting the hell out of there.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.000
As soon as you could.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.000
Yeah.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.000
And why was that?

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:59.000
Because I didn't like Virginia.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:02.000
And I shouldn't say that on camera.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:06.000
Because Virginia has many fine qualities. I have to put that part in here.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:12.000
I was too immature to really appreciate what was happening.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
I was too immature.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:18.000
Did you ever experience other parts of this outfit and the deep stuff?

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:22.000
No. No. That was enough.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
Yeah.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.000
Would you be around a little bit?

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:30.000
But I want to follow this when you finished it.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:32.000
You graduated.

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
And then where did you go from there?

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:36.000
School wise?

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:38.000
You said you wanted to get the hell out of here.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:41.000
Oh, yeah. I went to DC. My dad lived in DC.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:43.000
And I had a little boyfriend.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:46.000
Well, young man, boy friend.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:49.000
And my mother kept saying, come back to California.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:52.000
I said, Mama, when I go back, I'm not going back to San Diego.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:55.000
I don't like San Diego. It's too country.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:57.000
San Diego is flat.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:00.000
I said, I'm going home to San Francisco.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
She says, Claudette, please come back.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.000
She says, I'll tell you what.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:06.000
I'll pay your way back.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:10.000
And if you don't like it, you can go back to DC or San Francisco.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:13.000
Well, I came back and started partying.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:15.000
I'm a kid. I'm partying.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:17.000
I was a child.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:19.000
I was a child.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:21.000
I was a child.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:24.000
So I was stuck there for two years.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:27.000
Another city I didn't like.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:29.000
Then I moved to L.A.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:32.000
Because I'm partying in L.A.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:34.000
I have friends here.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.000
This is doing a summertime.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:38.000
I love dancing.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.000
And I thought, I'll dance all summer.

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:41.000
Go to all these parties.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:44.000
And then I'll go up to San Francisco and get a job.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:47.000
And what did you do for work?

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:52.000
My last job was California Assembly Bill 922,

00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:54.000
which is an expulsion counselor for L.A.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:58.000
Law San Jose Unified School District, L.A.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:23:59.000
USDA.

00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:01.000
So did you work for the school semester here?

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:02.000
Career.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:07.000
Well, I taught people working for masters.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.000
You know I have a doctorate in human behavior.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:13.000
So I taught graduate students career psychology.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:16.000
California Lutheran University and California Lutheran University.

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:19.000
What did you do?

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:22.000
At California Lutheran University.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:24.000
So back to California?

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:25.000
Yeah.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:28.000
Well, my master's at USC.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:31.000
I'm a California person.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:33.000
So what?

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:36.000
I do want to ask what he tells about the students.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.000
But let's stay in California for a minute.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:39.000
Okay.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:44.000
So what did that experience that you went through there?

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:49.000
But both as a student, it is just experiencing that side of you

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:54.000
and Crowley was kind of different from maybe from where you were raised.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:59.000
And then going through the sit-ins there and all that and coming back.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:01.000
What did you take away from that?

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:04.000
What did you bring back to California?

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:08.000
That the will of justice turned slowly, really and truly.

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:11.000
It's slowly, you know.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:16.000
And I often thought, would I do it again?

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:18.000
Yeah, I would do it again.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:20.000
I would do it again.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:21.000
Yeah.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.000
It did hurt me job-wise.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:27.000
I went for a job in DC.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:30.000
And the guy said, I have to hire you.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:33.000
But because you made a high score in the exam.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:36.000
But I don't think you would be happy here.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:41.000
He says, I see you've been involved in civil rights.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:45.000
And because I always put down that I have an arrest record.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:51.000
And then for Los Angeles Unified School District, I took the written exam ten times, never flunked the written.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:55.000
They flunked me on the training and experience.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:26:01.000
So I was working for the county school district before I came to Los Angeles Unified School District.

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:05.000
And I asked the superintendent of the counties, he liked me as a person.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:09.000
I said, Mr. Tollin, can you find out why they won't hire me in LA?

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:10.000
And he did.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.000
He says, you have an arrest record for sit-in.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:15.000
And they think you're going to be a problem.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:20.000
And I finally got in because somebody mistakenly sent me a contract.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.000
I think it was my guardian angel.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:23.000
I really do.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
I think somebody saw what was happening.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:30.000
I'm just guessing, maybe a black secretary in Santa Piper Out.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:33.000
You know.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:36.000
So it's here.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
You want to talk more about the sit-ins.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:42.000
And I guess I don't talk a lot about it because I think in my...

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:46.000
I think I've suppressed that it was uncomfortable.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:47.000
Very uncomfortable.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:50.000
And it hurts to this day.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:51.000
You know.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:53.000
What is it that's about it, say, think?

00:26:53.000 --> 00:27:02.000
Because it hurts because many people's attitude have not changed, you know?

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:10.000
And also, when I see these black kids, not going to school, it hurts me to my heart.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.000
Not voting.

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:16.000
You know, don't they realize they need an education.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:18.000
They have to vote.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:21.000
And many of them are not doing it.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:23.000
And I want to cry.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:25.000
You know.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:28.000
I really want to cry.

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:33.000
You told me before we started thinking back to these times, when do you feel very emotional?

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:36.000
I was wondering what exactly we were thinking about.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:37.000
Yeah.

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:41.000
The whole thing in life, but the way the situation is today.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:48.000
And also, with Obama being president, many feelings have come to surface.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:53.000
Many of what other people feel have come to surface in a negative fashion.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:55.000
And I don't like that.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:28:03.000
You know, the screaming out during sessions, calling him names, comparing him to Hitler and so forth.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:06.000
And I do know you always need a top dog.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:08.000
I understand that.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:12.000
And it will be, I mean, if we get rid of race, it'll be size, height.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:13.000
It will be something.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:14.000
Color eyes.

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:17.000
You know.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:21.000
When my brother came back from Switzerland, he was the man behind Henry Kissinger.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:24.000
And Henry Kissinger and a Henry Kissinger.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:27.000
He came back and he says, Claudette, you know.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:33.000
He says, this stuff is BS.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:34.000
I said, what?

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:35.000
He said, the racial stuff.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:37.000
He says, we have world problems.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:38.000
He was really upset.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:41.000
He says, we have world problems to contend with.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:42.000
You know.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:45.000
So you come from a panel of serious achievers.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:46.000
Yeah.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:47.000
I do.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:48.000
With the emphasis on education.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:49.000
Yeah.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:53.000
And any insight into that?

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:54.000
No.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:55.000
Not at all.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:56.000
Not at all.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:57.000
No.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:00.000
I'm glad I did.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:01.000
Yeah.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:02.000
Yeah.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:11.000
And your work in the school district at a counselor, were there racial issues that came up in the industry?

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:12.000
Yeah.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:20.000
In fact, I was so angry, I wrote a letter, three page type written, a computer written letter.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:24.000
And they're going to say it's not racial, but it is.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:30.000
We did expulsions for kids who brought knives, guns, drugs and so forth.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:31.000
Okay.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:33.000
We had a hearing.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:41.000
And if we found this to be so, then we told you you were straight expel or suspended expel.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:47.000
Which meant you're either kicked out of the school district or you go to a special school.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:56.000
We had a kid who, without any names, of course, who was involved and very involved in drugs.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:02.000
But because his parents had money, he was white.

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:04.000
They didn't kick him out.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.000
And I was so angry.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:08.000
And I was one of three on the committee.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.000
And I told the other two committee people who were white.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:14.000
I said, you know, he's guilty.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:18.000
And they said, well, he's going to go to college.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:23.000
I said, so, well, we judge it on a case by case.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:26.000
I said, yeah, I said, don't feed that to me.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:29.000
You know, that's like saying, oh, you're so good, you can do that.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:31.000
I said, don't do that to me.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:34.000
I said, the kid is guilty.

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:40.000
So I wrote a letter saying the inner city kids who are not going to go to college

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:45.000
who do the same thing or not as much will be expelled.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:48.000
So it's there.

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:50.000
No.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:54.000
Tell me to this.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:57.000
How did you feel when a woman was elected?

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:59.000
I was elated because he was intelligent.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.000
Not because he was only black.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
I have to put black too.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:05.000
Because he was intelligent, knowledgeable.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:11.000
And I felt he was going to do the best he could for everyone.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:14.000
You know, not just black people, everyone.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:18.000
You can't have someone doing for one group.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:21.000
And not the whole.

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:26.000
Were you in working with the school district during Boston period?

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:28.000
Yeah.

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:30.000
I was in black.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:32.000
I was on one of the committees and I asked a question.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:36.000
I said, why are you only busing the black kids?

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:40.000
And the person who was in charge said, did you hear what I said?

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:42.000
He shut me up.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:45.000
He says, did you hear what I said?

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:47.000
Right now we're busing the black kids.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:48.000
And that was it.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:51.000
And he talked over me.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:53.000
Yeah.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.000
And that is how it happened.

00:31:56.000 --> 00:32:04.000
You know, there are the ones who had to get up early, come home late, you know, drive far.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:06.000
I know where I lived in LA.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:11.000
I lived in view park, which had the number one elementary school academically in my area.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:17.000
Because the people who lived in my area were educators, doctors, lawyers, black people mostly.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:20.000
And our school was top.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:22.000
My kids went to private school, went to the French school.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:29.000
But anyway, they bus the kids from the school and no parent would put a kid on the bus.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:31.000
They said, why should we bus our kids?

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:34.000
Our kids have had integrated experiences.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:36.000
They've gone to Europe.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:38.000
They've, you know, they've been to the stories.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:40.000
They don't need to go to a white school.

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:45.000
Well, what the school district was was, was take out every other grade.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:48.000
So you had the bus shed kid away.

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:50.000
Right.

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:55.000
Was that one of the reasons why you sent your kids to private school?

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:57.000
No, I just did.

00:32:57.000 --> 00:32:59.000
I sent them to the French school.

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:01.000
I just did.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:03.000
They ended up at public school eventually.

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:04.000
Oh, they did?

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:05.000
Yeah.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:07.000
And which school?

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:08.000
You know, Palisades Charter High School?

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:09.000
Yeah.

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:10.000
That's where my sister went.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:11.000
Oh, really?

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:12.000
Yeah.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:14.000
And had an okay experience there?

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:15.000
Yeah.

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:17.000
Yeah.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:20.000
My kids don't see things the way I see things anyway.

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:27.000
Well, I mean, they have experienced my son used to be vice president of, uh, Fredo, uh,

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:30.000
Dr. Pepper in marketing.

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:36.000
Um, and before that, it was with Fredo Lays in marketing.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:40.000
And I don't want to say anything about different corporations.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:46.000
So I won't name the corporation, but he had a glass ceiling also, which, you know,

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:52.000
did you talk as you were raising your own children?

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:55.000
Did you talk to them at the experiences that you would have?

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:58.000
I did not.

00:33:58.000 --> 00:33:59.000
No.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:05.000
You know, my mother didn't tell me, well, she would show me these history books.

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:08.000
And I would see and read in the history books.

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:14.000
But she didn't want to prejudice me against people, which I can appreciate.

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:17.000
And I didn't want to do that to my children either.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:23.000
I know I took them out of school, uh, an ice date home that day and took on Martin Luther King's birthday.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:26.000
I would take them to the museum, you know.

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:30.000
That was the big black thing that we did, I guess.

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:34.000
Before it was a national holiday, you know.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:35.000
Right.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:40.000
What about getting positive, which is a black people in schools?

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:44.000
It's like that wasn't happening for your children?

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:48.000
You know, I don't think any more than I got.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.000
Yeah.

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:53.000
Because I don't think so.

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:59.000
No, I was on the book committee with Los Angeles Unified School District and I said, why is this

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:03.000
page with the black person on it at the end of the chapter?

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:06.000
And it was myth-hoofling.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:10.000
Because when we send the books down south, we tear that page out,

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.000
but we don't include that page.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:16.000
I said, but I've read the chapter and it has nothing to do with the chapter.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:20.000
I said, you're just stuck a black person in there to sell your book.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:21.000
You know.

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:24.000
Yeah.

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:30.000
I'm going to jump to this for the big question, I guess, which is.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.000
Oh, this is reflecting on this.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:33.000
It's no really.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.000
Yeah, well, my reflection is not good.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:36.000
Right.

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:42.000
Because the project that we're working on is on the civil rights.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:43.000
Civil rights.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:44.000
Right.

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:49.000
And I'm just curious, what is the civil rights movement to you?

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:52.000
Because I know it can be defined in different ways.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:58.000
And I'm sort of interested being the experiences that you had.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:02.000
Whether you see yourself as part of it, is it still going on?

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.000
What is the civil rights movement?

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:13.000
I think today the kids, especially in LA, they're not concerned about civil rights.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:17.000
It's La La Land.

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:22.000
What shoes do you have on, what purse, what brand name?

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:28.000
Whether you can rap play ball or basketball or football or jewelry or a car.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:32.000
It's a different story and that's black, white, green, or yellow.

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:38.000
You know, regardless of the race or they're involved in superficial things that won't last,

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:42.000
I don't think.

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:47.000
To me, you know, I moved up here and I kept my house in LA.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:50.000
I said, in case they burn across them, they mean white people.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:52.000
Burn across on my lawn.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:53.000
I'm moving.

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:55.000
I'm too old to fight now.

00:36:55.000 --> 00:36:56.000
You know?

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:57.000
I'm moving.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:59.000
And of course, they did not.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.000
They white people did not.

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:04.000
You thought that might have, where did Ohio help?

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:05.000
You thought that might happen?

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:15.000
Yeah, because I had read in the paper, is that a black kid in high school had nigger printed on her locker in Ohio.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.000
Not too long ago.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:27.000
Just before we moved up, which wasn't too long ago, we've been here nine years.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:32.000
And did that surprise, I mean, so hearing about an overt incident or racism like that,

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:36.000
and I don't know, a little time like, oh, hi, did that surprise you or is that sort of,

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:38.000
no, it didn't surprise me.

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:41.000
I didn't expect it, but I didn't surprise me.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:44.000
Yeah.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:47.000
And we talked about this a little bit on camera, but I wonder if you could tell me what,

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:52.000
what life is like in a town like this for an African person?

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:55.000
I guess it's like anything for any white person.

00:37:55.000 --> 00:38:00.000
I mean, it's a small town that closes up when the sun goes down.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:02.000
It has one block of downtowns.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:07.000
It has a lot of boutiques that are very expensive, and a lot of little restaurants.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:14.000
It has a theater that gets first-class movies because of all the directors that live here.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:19.000
It has two live theaters.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:23.000
And one theater, the local people play in, and the other theater, I don't know who plays.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:26.000
I don't go to them anymore.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:30.000
I go to LA.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:31.000
The club's closed.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:34.000
You can go in a club and take your child and your dog.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:41.000
There's one club next to the movie, and it's a nice little place, you know.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:43.000
It's nice.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:44.000
It's nice.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:47.000
Yeah, there are walking trails and horse trails.

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:51.000
And the helicopters are not ghetto copters.

00:38:51.000 --> 00:38:54.000
They are private helicopters.

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:58.000
That was one thing I have to just say that it gave us a beer just in Los Angeles.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:00.000
I hadn't been in Los Angeles for 20 years.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:04.000
It was something else to see the sky full of helicopters at Camp Nou.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:07.000
That's right.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:13.000
I knew how to work the projects, and if I had to go in them, I knew if the helicopters were overhead.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:20.000
If it's too late in the day, you don't go in, you know.

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:23.000
So did you do any of your jobs?

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:25.000
Did you do home visits?

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:34.000
Not as an expulsion counselor, but before that, I was making home calls.

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:41.000
As a job at another counselor, PSA, pupil services, and I tend, which expulsion was under that PSA, but it was a different...

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:46.000
I don't know how many jobs under PSA.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:52.000
I would make home calls, but you learn how to make home calls, you know.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:59.000
You learn when you knew on what we call Mother's Day when the people get their welfare checks, you don't go in.

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:04.000
Different days, and things, you know.

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:07.000
What happened on welfare check day?

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:12.000
The people weren't going to be home. They're busy.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:16.000
Cool.

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:19.000
So do you think, again, this is better?

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:22.000
Yes, I know because that's what you're doing.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:24.000
Yeah.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:28.000
What do you think we are now, or how do you feel about where we are?

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:30.000
I thought about that.

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:35.000
I think they say the more things change, the more they stay the same.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:41.000
I think things are, we have code words now, you know.

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:48.000
It's like living in California now. It's covert.

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:51.000
So, excuse me.

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:59.000
But my neighbor, when we go out to eat, we're going out to eat next Monday, four of us.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:04.000
My neighbor let me, oh, when I moved in here, my neighbor sent me a pie, which I thought was very nice.

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:07.000
In another neighbor gave me some fruit.

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:12.000
Anyway, my neighbor said, oh, I'm from some southern state.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:17.000
And she said it again to let me know, I think, that, hey, I'm okay.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:21.000
I'm a human being, you know.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:24.000
Because she told me that.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:27.000
Yeah.

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:31.000
I didn't answer your question.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:36.000
And I have pondered that question, where are we today?

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:47.000
Yeah, the black kids don't have to go into education, social work, ministry, whatever the jobs were that we could get.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:53.000
If you notice you ask an old person like me, I'm 73, what did you do?

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:56.000
They're all in education.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:59.000
Because that's the only thing we could do.

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:03.000
All the black men were at the post office, you know, with degrees.

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:06.000
Today you can get other jobs, fortunately.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:10.000
I don't know how high you're going, but you can get other jobs.

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:16.000
So, let me ask about your graphics and experience.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:21.000
Women in your program with other black students in your program.

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:25.000
USC didn't have many blacks, but, you know, there were other blacks.

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:29.000
And USC, you had a few.

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:34.000
A few. You didn't know not many.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:36.000
And the experience was fine.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:41.000
I didn't feel any racism at all.

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:48.000
I just, and from that experience that you had, Virginia, you knew you were still thinking, especially the city and experience.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:56.000
Did you, do that come back to you that actually did you draw on that experience at all and lay the part of your own?

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:58.000
Draw on it in which way?

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:01.000
I don't know. I would just leave it open to you.

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:07.000
There were times that that came back to you, or that you took something from that experience,

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:11.000
that made an influence where you, what you did later.

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:20.000
I think it opened me to be more respectful in my mind of people of different cultures.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:24.000
I call Richmond a different culture.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:30.000
To be respectful and to appreciate differences, we all can't be alike.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:34.000
And to appreciate where I am at the moment.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:38.000
At that time, I was so, my God, I can't stand Richmond.

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:43.000
I was the people, they're backwards. I'm judging. They weren't backwards. I was backwards.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:46.000
They were fine.

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:50.000
What was it like for you going back to the reunion?

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:55.000
Richmond hasn't changed. It still, it looks the same to me.

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:58.000
And yet they said, I don't know.

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:02.000
When I saw downtown, I said, my gosh, this place is the same.

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:11.000
I like visiting, but I'm going to live in California. I'm sure they're glad I'm here.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:15.000
Would you send your own children to the predominantly white colleges?

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:21.000
My son went to Union, but he didn't like it. He says, Mom, I can't take it. It's too country.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:23.000
But he did go to Morehouse.

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:24.000
Oh, he did?

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:25.000
Yeah, for undergrad.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:30.000
And then that school in Carolina, I told you for for grad.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:35.000
Was that going to a, to a, historically, back college, that's something that you thought might be important?

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:41.000
I wanted both my children to go. But as I told you, my daughter was on a 6-15, I think, when she started.

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:42.000
She was too young.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:43.000
Yeah.

00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:47.000
And my son, I think, was 16 or 17 yet.

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:49.000
You know, too young.

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:51.000
So they went to college, you know.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:52.000
But he was ready.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:53.000
Yeah.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:56.000
She said she was too mature, immature.

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:59.000
But she knew she was.

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:01.000
Don't you want to switch one?

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:02.000
Yeah.

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:03.000
Right.

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:04.000
Right.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:05.000
Yeah.

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:11.000
What did I take out of it?

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:18.000
Well, as I said, I really had my eyes opened when I went to the reunion 50th, the 50th year reunion for the sit-in people.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:23.000
And I had thought about it too about how I was so judgmental.

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:29.000
I remember an old black lady saying to me, honey, why are you guys marching for this?

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:32.000
You need to march for better jobs.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:34.000
And I thought, are you a silly old lady?

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:36.000
She must have been every bit of 50.

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:40.000
You know, why are you asking me this silly question?

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:45.000
I didn't say that to her, but I was thinking that, or we're not ready yet.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:49.000
I don't think, but when are you going to be ready?

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:50.000
Yeah.

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:57.000
So you really, you were involved in the very early sit-in.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:03.000
And did you, and left for the meeting, not too long after that?

00:46:03.000 --> 00:46:05.000
Well, I graduated in the 62.

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:06.000
Okay.

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:07.000
So a couple more years.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:08.000
Yeah.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:14.000
Did you follow what was going on in either back enrichment or in other parts of the South?

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:15.000
Yeah, oh, yeah.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:16.000
Oh, yeah, definitely.

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:24.000
Yeah, in fact, I was here, which is not quite the sit-ins, but the March on Washington, I was here.

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:30.000
And I told my husband, gee, I want to go to the March on Washington.

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:31.000
I really did.

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:34.000
You know, and my brother would keep me informed.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:40.000
He says, Claudette, today, people are meeting at the White House in planning strategy with President John F. Kennedy.

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:42.000
I say, you're kidding.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:45.000
He says, yeah.

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:52.000
So, yeah.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:54.000
You know, I'm sorry, I can't do more.

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:58.000
You know, when you get old, I swear, your mind, they say your mind is the first thing to go.

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.000
It's going.

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:03.000
I don't know.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:06.000
I don't know what you're supposed to do.

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:16.000
Just to follow on that, I was thinking of, do you remember your reactions to the legislation that I passed?

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:18.000
So, right to act, the voting rights act.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:21.000
I was extremely happy.

00:47:21.000 --> 00:47:28.000
Of course, it doesn't take much to make me happy, though.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:35.000
How does that relate to what we were saying before about, maybe you can change rules, but can you change parts of the mind?

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:40.000
Did you think that those, why did you think those acts were important?

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:49.000
Well, you know, well, as I said, first of all, you have to educate people.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:58.000
And maybe, hopefully, through education, people will change their way of thinking, hopefully.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:06.000
Maybe people will get out to vote if they can, if they don't put, they, I keep saying they, the party said be, black or white,

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:13.000
put stumbling blocks in the way, hopefully.

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:15.000
You have so many people that don't care.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:17.000
So, what difference does my vote make?

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:21.000
It's not going to change anything anyway.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:26.000
I remember the situation just in the last few days where it seems like the voting rights act might be challenging.

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:28.000
What was your reaction to that?

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.000
Good. Let's take it all the way up.

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:39.000
You see what happens. Good. Good.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:41.000
Good. Yeah.

00:48:41.000 --> 00:48:43.000
Yeah, that's fine.

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:48.000
As my uncle and my aunt, let's have a good old fight.

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:52.000
My uncle and aunt love knock them down fights legally.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:55.000
Yeah.

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:57.000
Yeah.

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:03.000
Oh, that brings one out of the question, which was how did your family react about your involvement in the city?

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:08.000
Well, I called my uncle and he used to call me screwball.

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:12.000
He said screwball, talk to Martin A. Martin.

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:14.000
That was the attorney handling it.

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:16.000
That was his friend.

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:20.000
And I talked to attorney Martin.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:22.000
I said, my uncle told me to talk to you.

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:24.000
He said, who's your uncle? I said, Jay Hugo, Matt.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:26.000
He said, oh, I know him.

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:28.000
I said, he says for you to take care of me.

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:30.000
He says, okay, I will.

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:33.000
And I felt very happy and giddy about the city.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:42.000
I didn't, it was depressing the whole, as I said, the whole thing of being in that patty wagon.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
It was not clean.

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:47.000
And then being in the jail wasn't clean.

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:50.000
And then the courtroom was segregated.

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:51.000
And it was smelly.

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:54.000
And the guy who came in was nasty and smelly.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:57.000
I just thought, I'm losing my mind.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:49:59.000
This is hell.

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:03.000
I really thought I didn't know what hell was at that time.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:07.000
But you said you were also giddy.

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:10.000
I was giddy because I'm changing the world.

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:12.000
It's going to change now.

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:13.000
I'm going to court.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:14.000
It's going to change.

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:16.000
We're all going to be happy.

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:20.000
And it's going to be black people are going to stand up.

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:23.000
And the white people are going to be okay.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:26.000
I mean, we're not going to sit down and eat ice cream together.

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:29.000
But at least you're going to respect that I can sit down here.

00:50:29.000 --> 00:50:32.000
So you got the support of your uncle?

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:33.000
Oh, yeah.

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:36.000
And my aunt, my aunt called me from New York.

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:37.000
She said, yeah.

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:40.000
Were there others that were fearful for you?

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:41.000
No, nobody.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:42.000
Nobody.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:45.000
My mother, my stepfather, nobody.

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:47.000
Now, not at all.

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:49.000
So what was the reaction you got?

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:51.000
They were very happy.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:53.000
And my uncle says, Claudette,

00:50:53.000 --> 00:50:56.000
things are not going to change as fast as you think.

00:50:56.000 --> 00:50:58.000
It takes time.

00:50:58.000 --> 00:50:59.000
It takes time.

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:01.000
Did you believe him?

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:05.000
Yeah, because I knew he was doing that in Norfolk.

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:09.000
Yeah, I believe too.

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:16.000
Do you feel that the family that you came from prepared you for?

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:18.000
What were you going to involve in it in some way?

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:19.000
I'm sure.

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:20.000
I'm sure.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:26.000
Without knowing it, you give your children their values.

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:29.000
Covertly and overtly, both ways.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:30.000
Yeah.

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:35.000
In fact, my mother always said, the squeaky will gets the attention

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:36.000
whether it's bad or good.

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:42.000
So I guess I was a squeaky will.

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:45.000
And have you stayed in touch with people from Virginia?

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:47.000
You went to the reunion?

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:48.000
No.

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:50.000
I saw only Charles.

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:52.000
And that was by mistake.

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:54.000
Well, not by mistake.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:58.000
I saw him on TV doing black history month.

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:02.000
And I said, that's Charles and I went online and found him.

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:05.000
And had you been aware of what he had been doing all these years?

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:06.000
No.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:07.000
No.

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:09.000
What was your life?

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:11.000
What was your life when you were in?

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:13.000
He was my boyfriend.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:15.000
Oh, come on.

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:17.000
He was a Baptist minister.

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:20.000
And at that time, I was a pseudo Catholic.

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:23.000
I went to Catholic Church in Richmond.

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:27.000
And I knelt down and everyone came in the pew.

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:30.000
They looked over and saw me and got up and laughed.

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:33.000
And I said, now my faith is not that good to start out with.

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:35.000
And you guys are not helping it any.

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:38.000
I'm thinking, you know.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:41.000
And people are going to hate me when I say this because I'm spiritual now.

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:44.000
Whatever that means.

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:46.000
So I told the priest after Mass.

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:50.000
I said, you know, people came in when I say people, white people.

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:53.000
People came in the pew where I was.

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:57.000
And they looked over and saw me and got up and laughed.

00:52:57.000 --> 00:52:59.000
I said, then an old lady came.

00:52:59.000 --> 00:53:01.000
There was no place to sit.

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:03.000
And she came late and saw me.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:05.000
She knelt down beside me.

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:07.000
Then she saw me and got up and laughed.

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:09.000
He says, my child pray for her.

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:12.000
And I thought, well, I'm not going to church anymore.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:15.000
I have to pray for people and you can't tell them.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:18.000
You know, doing a Mass.

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:19.000
Yeah.

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:21.000
No, it's the last time you went to that church.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:22.000
Yeah.

00:53:22.000 --> 00:53:23.000
Yeah.

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:26.000
And as I said, my faith wasn't too strong anyway.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:30.000
So it didn't take much to make it go.

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:33.000
So what was your own Charles Charade like?

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:35.000
He was nice.

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:38.000
I would go with him when he preached down in the country.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:41.000
Like an intern preaching at these country churches.

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:44.000
And he used to say, darn, you Catholic girl.

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:47.000
He would call me a Catholic girl.

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:48.000
Yeah.

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:51.000
When I say boyfriend, girlfriend, we weren't tight, tight,

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:54.000
but we were boyfriend, girlfriend.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.000
Yeah.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:54:00.000
And had you seen preaching like that before?

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:01.000
Yeah.

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:05.000
I went with my girlfriend in San Francisco to two or three churches.

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:11.000
But they weren't emotional, you know?

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:14.000
But they did sing songs.

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:18.000
I mean, you know, songs with a beat to it.

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:19.000
Yeah.

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:21.000
I like that now.

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:22.000
Yeah.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:23.000
Yeah.

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:25.000
I don't know the beat.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:27.000
Now you need to find your El Haido.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:28.000
Well, no.

00:54:28.000 --> 00:54:29.000
No.

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:31.000
You can get it on YouTube.

00:54:31.000 --> 00:54:32.000
Yeah.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:33.000
Yeah.

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:40.000
What do you have any other questions?

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:43.000
No, I've never been to a lot of Brown.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:45.000
Yeah, I'm sorry.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:47.000
My memory is really bad.

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:48.000
I am so sorry.

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:52.000
You did mention that it was very emotional time.

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:55.000
What was the access to made so emotional?

00:54:55.000 --> 00:55:01.000
Well, I felt like I wanted to cry because when I think about what has been

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:07.000
been happening in the past and what is happening now, I'm not too far.

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:13.000
I'm not too sure that we're that far from the past and now with things that

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:19.000
I went online to see the insults that were hold at Obama.

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:25.000
And I had to stop because there were so very many of them.

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:30.000
And all of them, some of them are right out in his face.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:31.000
But why?

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:36.000
I used to think the poor of the person was the more they would hold insults.

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:38.000
But that's not true.

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:43.000
They can have 10 PhDs and do the same thing.

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:49.000
And as I said, I want to cry about my black children not voting.

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:53.000
White kids too don't vote, unfortunately.

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:55.000
Not going to school.

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:57.000
Drugs are rampant.

00:55:57.000 --> 00:56:00.000
Oh, hi has a big drug problem.

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:02.000
What are we doing?

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:04.000
What are we rearing today?

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:07.000
Where are we going?

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:09.000
You're not voting mostly.

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:10.000
Yeah.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:11.000
Yeah.

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:12.000
Yeah.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:15.000
I don't know.

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:22.000
I don't think we're obviously through this project where in some way so,

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:25.000
we're also taking stock.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:29.000
It's a time to reflect.

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:35.000
Not only on what was done and sit into the 19th and 16th, but where are we?

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:37.000
Sometimes I don't want to.

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:40.000
Reflect.

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:43.000
I told, because it's uncomfortable.

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:50.000
I told my husband, I said, you know, I'm not filling this paper out before I go to bed.

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:53.000
Because I won't be able to sleep.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:57:00.000
When I put my uncle down in my aunt, down thinking about the things they were involved in and so forth.

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:03.000
What do you think about how they would respond?

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:07.000
No, I know what they went through.

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:10.000
You know.

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:15.000
I did tell you, maybe my aunt integrated the bus line, a greyhound bus line,

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:21.000
and the courts had already said it should be not separate but equal together.

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:23.000
And they did not integrate it.

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:25.000
It was in Virginia.

00:57:25.000 --> 00:57:28.000
And my aunt told my mother was visiting.

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:33.000
My aunt told my mother and another sister, come on, we're going to go to DC from Virginia.

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:35.000
And we're going by bus.

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:37.000
And my mother says, why?

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:38.000
Let's drive.

00:57:38.000 --> 00:57:41.000
And my aunt said, no, we're going by bus.

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:43.000
Because we don't take the greyhound.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:46.000
Anyway, it took the greyhound and my aunt got off.

00:57:46.000 --> 00:57:48.000
She says, you keep going to DC.

00:57:48.000 --> 00:57:54.000
Call Hugo, that's my uncle, and call Paul, Adam Clayton Powell,

00:57:54.000 --> 00:57:56.000
because I'm going to get arrested.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:04.000
And she did, because she said in the white section, but the courts made them obey the law.

00:58:04.000 --> 00:58:06.000
You know.

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:12.000
That was something that surprised me about the movement, was how much, once the law was in effect,

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:16.000
how much testing of the law had to be done all over the country?

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:17.000
Right.

00:58:17.000 --> 00:58:18.000
Yeah.

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:22.000
In fact, something was on the news recently about some little southern town,

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:24.000
that I don't know what it was.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:25.000
Did you see it?

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:26.000
I missed it.

00:58:26.000 --> 00:58:27.000
Oh.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:28.000
Yeah.

00:58:28.000 --> 00:58:35.000
But I know even here in California, I know not to go in some cities.

00:58:36.000 --> 00:58:37.000
To that, really.

00:58:37.000 --> 00:58:38.000
Heck, yes.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:39.000
Yeah.

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:43.000
Because you know what kinds of things do you think would happen?

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:48.000
Well, for example, I was going to a city, and I didn't want to name the city.

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:52.000
And I passed to a little place, Canyon Country, down that way.

00:58:52.000 --> 00:58:57.000
And I got lost before I had the GPS.

00:58:57.000 --> 00:58:59.000
And my daughter was with me.

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:02.000
I said, we can't stop at that little club there.

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:04.000
I said, it looks like a little red net club.

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:05.000
We can't stop there.

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:07.000
I said, do you know what I'm talking about?

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:10.000
She says, mom, I know.

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:12.000
I don't know what she knows.

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:14.000
She said she knows.

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:19.000
And because you can fill it, you know?

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:23.000
And that's something that, in some ways, hasn't changed.

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:28.000
I mean, I'm sure you could sense those places throughout your life.

00:59:28.000 --> 00:59:29.000
Right.

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:32.000
And when you intellectualize it, you get in trouble.

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:35.000
You have to fill it in your gut and go with your gut.

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:38.000
Yeah.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:40.000
Well, that's just it.

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:43.000
You can decide a lot of things in what's for it.

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:44.000
Right.

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:46.000
But the feelings are another whole thing.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:47.000
Absolutely.

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:50.000
And that's true for man, period, in everything he does.

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
You know, regardless of race.

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:54.000
You know.

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:57.000
And in some way, you rely on a community, right?

00:59:57.000 --> 01:00:00.000
And you can navigate these things.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:02.000
And some of it's difficult.

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:04.000
I would think difficult in a place like Ohio.

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:06.000
The community isn't that large.

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:07.000
No.

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:08.000
But I felt it in Ohio.

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:09.000
But I move on.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:11.000
You know, you don't have to like me.

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:12.000
That's fine.

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:13.000
For it.

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:14.000
Yeah.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:18.000
Do you remember when they had The Negro Motorist Green Book?

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:19.000
No, I know.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:20.000
Oh, you're too young.

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:22.000
What's that?

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:24.000
When you traveled, we were little.

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:25.000
I was little.

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:29.000
And my parents used to go to AAA and get, you know,

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:31.000
how they draw the map for you.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:33.000
Well, they had a special book for black people,

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:35.000
where you could stay.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:37.000
Yeah.

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:43.000
Because when we traveled, my parents sometimes would stop at a black person's house.

01:00:43.000 --> 01:00:48.000
And say, do you know where black people can stay when we traveled down south?

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:52.000
And they would say, Mrs. Jones has a room.

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:56.000
And we would go there, the stay overnight.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:00:57.000
Yes.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:01.000
Those are kind of things that people can't even imagine now.

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:02.000
You know?

01:01:02.000 --> 01:01:03.000
Yeah.

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:04.000
You have people.

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:06.000
I mean, there are people I talk with.

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:08.000
They seem like grownups and they were given born.

01:01:08.000 --> 01:01:09.000
Right.

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:10.000
They don't have a 2,000 year old.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:12.000
Yeah, they have no idea.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:13.000
Yeah.

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:14.000
That's true.

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:17.000
But it also says a lot about, I mean, essentially,

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:18.000
a triple A sort of formalized.

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:21.000
It processes a lot about how people adapt and take care of each other.

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:26.000
You know, that you could stop at someone's house and put you on.

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:27.000
Yeah.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:29.000
I mean, Mrs. Jones did put a trap word.

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:35.000
On the flip side, integration closed many black people's businesses.

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:36.000
Absolutely.

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:37.000
Yeah.

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:41.000
Peg Leg Bates had a place in the upper New York.

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:42.000
I can't think of what it's called.

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:44.000
People back east know it.

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:50.000
And I heard that the black people used to go there and stay overnight and have a good time.

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:52.000
And it closed when integration happened.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:56.000
Many of the black hotels and other places closed.

01:01:56.000 --> 01:01:57.000
Yeah.

01:01:57.000 --> 01:01:58.000
Yeah.

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:04.000
Are there other things that you think the black community lost during the integration?

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:09.000
I think some of the black kids don't know who they are, whatever that means, who they are.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:10.000
Yeah.

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:11.000
Yeah.

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:18.000
You know, my girlfriend is married to a Mexican fellow.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:24.000
And her kids told her, Mom, oh, you just think that because you're black.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:29.000
And, yeah, they don't know anything about her, really.

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:30.000
Yeah.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:32.000
That also means they don't identify.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:33.000
Right.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:34.000
Yeah.

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:35.000
Yeah.

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:36.000
Yeah.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:37.000
Yeah.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:46.000
We hear a lot of stories of, in some ways, stories of laws or even a nest challenge for.

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:48.000
A good old day.

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:49.000
Oh, black school.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:50.000
Yeah.

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:51.000
Yeah.

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:55.000
Looking at it as the little days, even, of course, there was a lot of.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:56.000
For that.

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:57.000
Right.

01:02:57.000 --> 01:02:58.000
Yeah.

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:06.000
You know, speaking of black, I have written the LA Times and various other newspapers about not capitalizing the word black.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:09.000
And I spelled it out why I felt it should be.

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:12.000
I said, white is generic.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:13.000
Black is not.

01:03:13.000 --> 01:03:17.000
When you say black, you only mean an American from Africa.

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:19.000
You don't mean a Jamaican.

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:21.000
You don't mean a Puerto Rican.

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:27.000
You only mean a person in America who is black.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:29.000
So it should be capitalized.

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:38.000
And I feel that it's in and insult when you see in the papers different groups of people and then a lower case letter of a black.

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:39.000
You know.

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:41.000
Yeah.

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:43.000
I wrote a letter.

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:50.000
Oh, also in that package, I have a letter that I wrote to this local paper and I'm surprised they printed it.

01:03:50.000 --> 01:04:00.000
They talked about two black women doing something fraudulent and it should you see them call the police.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:03.000
So I wrote them a long letter.

01:04:03.000 --> 01:04:06.000
I said, you named two black women.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:11.000
You have made it dangerous for me to walk downtown.

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:12.000
No description.

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:13.000
That's it.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:14.000
That was the only description.

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:16.000
Yeah, it's in that packet.

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:17.000
Yeah.

01:04:17.000 --> 01:04:18.000
Yeah.

01:04:18.000 --> 01:04:25.000
Have you written any other letters to the editor over the years or other issues that got under your schedule?

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:31.000
Only about the black issue have I written to the very, I wrote it to the LA Times and I'm always writing letters.

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:37.000
Well, but I write good letters to compliment people when they should be.

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:47.000
I felt I was writing my bicycle and I turned the corner too fast and for the first time I didn't have my helmet on and I hit my head on the fire hydrant around the corner.

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:51.000
And I'm down there crying like an ugly ugly thing just crying.

01:04:51.000 --> 01:04:54.000
And I look uglier than ugly when I cry.

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:57.000
And two men got out of their truck and they said, are you okay?

01:04:57.000 --> 01:05:00.000
I said, oh no, I'm crying.

01:05:00.000 --> 01:05:02.000
Why man held my hand as well?

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:04.000
Then I thought, oh god, you're looking uglier.

01:05:04.000 --> 01:05:05.000
Stop crying.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:07.000
So I stopped crying.

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:14.000
But you know, there were two white men helping a black lady or two men helping a female for that matter.

01:05:14.000 --> 01:05:15.000
Yeah.

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:17.000
So I haven't felt anything.

01:05:17.000 --> 01:05:20.000
Oh, I mean, I'm sure they're.

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:26.000
As I said, if I feel anything, I move on.

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:31.000
I might be wrapping up here.

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:34.000
Do you think about that?

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:40.000
You know, what you did at Virginia Union University and being part of this protest.

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:43.000
As something very historic, you did it being a participant.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:44.000
I do now.

01:05:44.000 --> 01:05:45.000
I didn't think it was.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:47.000
I thought it was something we were doing.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:51.000
You know, it was one of many people across the country.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:05:54.000
But I didn't realize it until afterwards.

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:57.000
In fact, I didn't realize it until I was at a school.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:05:59.000
And I was in the library.

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:04.000
And the lady says, Dr. Grinnell, do you know anything about the Civil Rights Movement?

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:06.000
And I said, yeah, I do.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:08.000
I said, I was in it.

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:09.000
She says, you were?

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:11.000
Oh, no, not a big deal.

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:14.000
You know, then I realized she's young.

01:06:14.000 --> 01:06:16.000
She's a young teacher.

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:19.000
And that's when it hit me.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:21.000
I guess it was a big deal.

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:22.000
Yeah.

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:26.000
That's a great finish in one, I think.

01:06:26.000 --> 01:06:27.000
Oh, thank you.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:29.000
Well, it wasn't a deal.

01:06:29.000 --> 01:06:30.000
Yeah, yeah.

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:34.000
Well, let me just ask you, was there anything that I didn't ask that you thought I might ask or that I should have asked?

01:06:34.000 --> 01:06:38.000
No, I'll think of it later on, but it probably won't be important anyway.

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:40.000
So, no.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:41.000
Well, thank you so much.

01:06:41.000 --> 01:06:42.000
But thank you.

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:43.000
I appreciate it.

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:46.000
And I'll tell you what you have to do while you're here since I made a cake for you guys.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:47.000
You have to eat it.

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:48.000
I made a pound cake.

01:06:48.000 --> 01:06:50.000
Well, whether you like it or not.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:06:51.000
You have to take off.

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:52.000
Okay.

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:55.000
You've done your sacrifice.

01:06:55.000 --> 01:07:04.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

